body:
I have been working for quite some time now on my [Debug Visualizer](https://marketplace.visualstudio.com/items?itemName=hediet.debug-visualizer) extension that visualizes values while debugging. I find it very helpful when working with TypeScript ASTs:

![](https://raw.githubusercontent.com/hediet/vscode-debug-visualizer/master/docs/demo.gif)

To do that, I had to fork node-debug2 and [send the `paused` event as custom event together with the current frame id](https://github.com/hediet/vscode-node-debug2/commit/a2a43db0b5926d81d02136482031f4229537d7bd#diff-d03a74f75ec189cbc7dd3d2e105fc9c9R998).
Without manually patching the node debug adapter, the extension could neither visualize local variables as it doesn't know the current frame id nor could it update the visualization when the next breakpoint is hit as there is no event for that that can be consumed by extensions.
I used the [`evaluation` request](https://github.com/microsoft/vscode/issues/42989) to evaluate the given expression.

It would be great if VS Code could provide an event `onExecutionStateChanged` with a signature similar to this:
```ts
vscode.debug.onExecutionStateChanged: Event<DebugSessionExecutionStateChangedEvent>;

type DebugSessionExecutionStateChangedEvent = {
   newState: "running" | "stopped";
} | {
   newState: "paused"
   newFrameId: number;
}
```
Such an event would enable extensions like mine that could highly improve the debugging experience!

- VSCode Version: 1.30.0
- OS Version: Windows

Steps to Reproduce:

1. Create an extension with the following files
`package.json`
```
{
    "name": "decorator-select",
    "description": "Decorator with Theme Selection colors",
    "publisher": "meme",
    "version": "1.0.0",
    "engines": {
        "vscode": "^1.30.0"
    },
    "activationEvents": [
        "onCommand:extension.decoratorselect"
    ],
    "contributes": {
        "commands": [
          {
            "command": "extension.decoratorselect",
            "title": "Decorator with Theme Selection colors"
          }
        ]
    },
    "main": "./index.js"
}
```
`index.js`
```
const vscode = require('vscode');

function activate(context) {
    var decorator = vscode.window.createTextEditorDecorationType( {
      color: new vscode.ThemeColor('editor.selectionForeground'),
      backgroundColor: new vscode.ThemeColor('editor.selectionBackground')
    });

    context.subscriptions.push(
        vscode.commands.registerCommand('extension.decoratorselect', () => {
            const editor = vscode.window.activeTextEditor;
            if (!editor) { return; }
            editor.setDecorations(decorator, [new vscode.Range(new vscode.Position(1, 0), new vscode.Position(1, 20))]);
        })
    );
};

function deactivate() {}

module.exports = {
    activate,
    deactivate
}
```
2. Load a file with some text (>30 chars) on line 2
3. Call command `"Decorator with Theme Selection colors"`
4. The decorated text has the foregroundColor equal to the backgroundColor. Except if you use the `High Contrast` Theme.

In a (Typescript) React project it is common to have both `.ts` files and `.tsx` files all result in `.js` files in the end. It is possible to exclude some of these, but to my search it did not seem possible to hide both these types of files. It would be nice to be able to hide derived resources (JS files in this case) based on more sophisticated expressions. 

One solution would be to allow multiple patterns. It might look something like:

    "files.exclude": {
        "**/*.js": {
            "when": [ "$(basename).ts", "$(basename).tsx" ]
        }
    },

Another way is to treat 'when' expression as regular expressions, like:

    "files.exclude": {
        "**/*.js": {
            "when": "$(basename).ts(x?)"
        }
    },
